Meet Sanele Shange. Sanele is the first black South African to qualify for the Ironman World Championship, and he finished his first race in Kona in 9 : 33 despite a crash during the bike that left him with a cracked helmet, bruised hip, and road rash. This young man has a huge future! And yep: swimming with dolphins is way better than crocodiles. Watch my full conversation with Sanele on the Babbittville YouTube channel --> link in bio

#ironmantri #triathlontraining #triathlon

Triathlon has such an incredible community. On Sunday evening, we had an amazing gathering with the Triathlon Club of San Diego, as we hosted the Ironman World Champion Chelsea Sodaro at our Challenged Athletes Foundation headquarters. Chelsea was awesome. Our conversation was filmed and is up on the Babbittville YouTube channel. We had some very special guests in the house, including February 1982 Ironman World Champion Kathleen McCartney. 40 years separates their victories, but the triathlon connection is timeless. We also had 2006 champion Michellie Jones, and Ironman co-founders Judy and John Collins. Love our triathlon community.

1 day left in 2022.
The number 1 strongest person I have ever known: the unstoppable Lauren Parker. And a reminder that ➡️ out of the darkness ➡️ comes light. 

Lauren won both Ironman World Championships in 2022 plus the ITU Paratriathlon World Championship in Abu Dhabi.
In 2021, Lauren won the 70.3 World Championship and took silver in the Paralympics. She now has two Ironman World Championships, one Ironman 70.3 World Championship, two ITU Paratriathlon World Championship titles, and a Paralympic silver medal since she was paralyzed on April 18, 2017. And Lauren has done all of this while in non-stop excruciating pain...with a smile on her face. As the tatoo on her arm exclaims: Kia Kaha. Forever Strong.

Watching Lauren complete the Ironman World Championship in Kona was the highlight of my year.

It was a great spectating weekend for me on beautiful Catalina Island for the @runcatalina @hitec Avalon 50/50. Happy #MedalMonday to everyone who took on the 50K or 50 mile run up and down and around the island. And up a little more just for fun. 😆 
Catalina Island has been a favorite place to race for me for years, running the March trail marathon over 20 times and doing the triathlon numerous times as well. But I had never been over for the January 50/50 race. Had an awesome time spectating, even finally got to see one of the island foxes. For all you ultra and trail runners out there, check out the Triple Crown belt buckle. This sweet hardware can be yours. Just complete the three races in a calendar year. Thanks Mike Bone and the amazing crew at Spectrum Sports for a great experience.

I've had the honor of running two Super Bowl ads. The first was for our documentary @we_are_triathletes_movie that aired in Glendive, Montana during the 2019 game. The one and only @rudygarciatolson. 
Thanks to the great marketing idea from buddy @markbealpr who first shared the idea with me of airing Super Bowl ads for clients in small markets.

Part 2: It's Super Bowl week, when everyone's attention turns to - the ads. 😀 I've had the honor of running two Super Bowl ads. Here's the second one. It ran last year on our awesome documentary on the incredible Landis Sims: the first quadruple amputee to make his high school varsity baseball team (spoiler alert). It aired in Cooperstown, New York, home of the Baseball Hall of Fame. So when everyone discusses their favorite ads from the Super Bowl, it's an easy answer for me.

Watching Lionel Sanders at the Super League Arena Games yesterday made me smile.

During the week leading into the race we heard from a number of folks doubting whether Lionel could be competitive in such a short, high intensity event racing against younger and faster athletes who focus on the shorter distances. There was a school of thought out there that said that he’d be embarrassed and he wouldn’t even make it to the finals
 
Anytime I hear the doubters, I think back to the first interview we did together on Babbittville Radio back in 2015. I get goosebumps listening to Lionel explain how triathlon saved his life while sharing the darkest moments of his journey up until that point.
 
I love stories of people who come back from their lowest lows to achieve greatness and Lionel is right at the very top of that list in my opinion.
 
He is now an icon in our sport, a husband, a father, and an entertainer. When you give this interview a listen I bet you will have a better understanding of why nothing scares or intimidates this man, especially something as trivial as jumping into a pool, riding a bike, or running on a treadmill.
Listen on the web: babbittville.com/lionel-sanders (link in Story)

Our great sport of Ironman Triathlon is built on the shoulders of great women.....from Day 1 women have played a significant role in shaping our sport, growing our sport, and showing the world that women can push the boundaries and do extraordinary things. Rest in Peace to the incredible Rick Hoyt. 
Dick and his son Rick are iconic figures, racing together, with dad pushing Rick in his chair, through some of the most brutal endurance events around. Yet while there may be a statue of them in Hopkinton now, it wasn’t always so easy for Dick and Rick to be accepted as athletes. But Dick and Rick are not two ordinary people, and the lives they have changed are unmeasurable! 

I took this photo in Kona before the 2017 parade when the Hall of Famers would walk together down Ali'i Drive. I love how you can see that wonderful spark in Rick's eyes. He had such an amazing spirit. I have a lot of great memories of joking with Rick throughout the years. He had an awesome sense of humor. I will deeply miss him. Thank you Rick for helping to make the world a better place. 

There is a Breakfast with Bob interview I filmed in Boston with Dick and Rick in 2018 on the Babbittville YouTube channel. Just search the channel for Rick Hoyt.

What an amazing weekend in San Diego spent with legends and good friends. 

1️⃣ First, we went to the 40 Years party for the world’s best swim coach Rob ‘Sickie’ Marcikic, who I started swimming with in the early 1980’s. Scott Tinley, Mark Allen, Scott Molina, Julie Moss, Kathleen McCartney, and so many others swam with Sickie over the years, and countless age groupers learned to love swimming because of him. He also wrote our Swim Lanes column for Competitor Magazine for years. His personality and creativity was the reason people loved jumping into a cold pool at 5 AM every morning!

2️⃣ Back in 1979, when the Iromman was a year old, a Navy SEAL and Vietnam vet by the name of Moki Martin created the Superfrog Triathlon on Coronado SEAL Base as a training race one month before the Ironman. Moki and I went head to head as age groupers until a tragic accident one morning left Moki with quadriplegia. But he continued putting on the Superfrog, and eventually I helped him sell the event to Ironman. The event was all about cold water, huge surf and a half marathon primarily in soft sand. Superfrog and Moki have always been about being tough. One of my prized possessions is a painting Moki did as a quadriplegic of six-time Ironman Dave Scott. It is on display in my living room and every time I look at it reminds me of my friend Moki Martin.

3️⃣ Kevin McCarey was an elite marathoner with a 2:12 PR who was an even better coach. His weekly running sessions at Ski Beach brought out the very best talent in San Diego and we spent a great week together at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney and we watched Michellie Jones, who he coached, bring home the silver medal in the first-ever Olympic triathlon. Kevin and I accompanied Michellie that evening as she made her way through public parks in Sydney where people were gathered to watch the Olympics on big screen TVs. When Michellie and that silver medal showed up it was pandemonium. Then we used that medal to bypass every line and every bouncer at every bar in Sydney.

To see these 3 amazing people over our Independence Weekend made me realize how truly blessed I am to know these three legends who I am lucky enough to call friends

The interview last night for our Tri Club of San Diego was pretty amazing. Everyone in the room took away amazing life lessons from the legend herself, Siri Lindley. I'll let everyone know when this interview goes live. I think you will love it!

A Look Back at 2023
52 weeks of celebrating the joys of swimming, biking, and running with the greatest people on the planet, and the honor of getting a front row seat to witness the transformative power of sport. Thank you to everyone who shared in such a memorable year: my racing buddies, our Breakfast with Bob viewers and sponsors, and all the amazing #TeamCAF athletes and supporters. 
1️⃣ It was an awesome, busy year of Breakfast with Bob: 230 interviews and 7 million minutes of viewing time. We traveled around the world:  70.3 Oceanside, XTERRA Oak Mountain, Challenge Roth, Ironman World Championship Nice, SuperLeague Malibu, and Ironman World Championship Kona. 
2️⃣ 15 races for me in 2023. Nothing better than starting your day in a transition area, then swimming, biking, and running, and topping it off talking story with all your race buddies. 
3️⃣ Started the year celebrating the greatest sport on the planet at the Global Triathlon Awards in Nice, France. Was humbled to be honored with the Lifetime Contributor award at a very special evening filled with great memories.
And, finally:
4️⃣ The highlight of my year: Our 30th annual Challenged Athletes Foundation San Diego Triathlon Challenge. We had over 150 challenged athletes join us for the weekend, and our amazing supporters raised over 5.3 million dollars to help keep challenged athletes in the game of life through sport. 
🔜 Ready to take another spin around the world of swimming, biking, and running in 2024. See you at the races!

Today is January 4, 2024, Dave Scott’s 70th birthday. When we talk about the greatest Ironman World Championship athletes of all time, The Man is right there at the top of the list. He won his first Ironman World Championship in the third running of the event in the island of Oahu in 1980 and 16 years later, at the age of 42, he came off the bike in something like 26th place, put together a 2:45 marathon and finished fifth. 

Let’s look at his firsts. He was the first person to go sub-11, sub-10, sub-9:30, sub-9:00, and sub-8:30 in Kona. He led the race wire-to-wire in both 1980 and in October of 1982. He was the first to go under 3:00 for the marathon, the first to go sub-2:55 and the first to go sub-2:50. When Mark Allen finally beat Mr. October in 1989 at IronWar, Dave broke his existing course record by 18 minutes and his run course record by around eight minutes. When Dave Scott returned to race Kona at the age of 40 after five years away from the race, he finished an unbelievable second to Greg Welch.

Here’s to a Happy 70th Birthday to the first inductee into the Ironman Hall of Fame, Mr. Dave Scott. Welcome to the 70-74 age group, Legend!!

It's the great Mark Allen's birthday today. The 6-time Ironman World Champion is an amazing speaker and I love chatting with the legendary Hall of Famer. I learn something from every conversation. Mark's Ironman career was filled with incredible performances, but it took years of heartbreak for those winning moments to come - and to be so meaningful. Mark came to Kona six times trying to win the Ironman and to beat Dave Scott and each time he came up empty. On his seventh try, it finally happened. And he went on to win the sport's biggest race another five times. In this segment from an interview in front of the Triathlon Club of San Diego, Mark takes us through his mindset in that iconic 1989 race we call Ironwar. There's probably 20 soundbites in this two minute video that you can take with you as reminders of how to successfully tackle any challenge. Happy birthday to The Grip!
